{"commentv2": 1, "number": 60, "id": 340063, "nreplies": 0, "sticky": 0, "user": "Zefyrus", "body": "The twilight of The Burning Crusade finds Illidan being farmed by thousands of guilds around the globe. That brings joy and satisfaction to the players/customers, however it's kind of an abuse and at some point destroys the prestige this tragic figure of Warcraft had; I think we can all agree that Illidan is a fantastic character, both from appearance and beliefs. Among the peace, he is the screech; he was driven by desire, the lust for power, but he remained Illidan. He's not the kind of classic bad guy that gets insane or loses his mind. He does what he does conciously; he's the type of character seen in many movies, read in many books. Illidan, in literature terms, represents that so called \"weakness\", every human has well hidden beneath his flesh: desire. In that case, the desire to dominate his surroundings and ultimately, everyone and everything.\r\nHistory, however has a strange way of marking these people (in real life) with the big red label \"MADMAN\". We all have desires. Of different kinds.\r\n\r\nThis might be a fantasy game but it is made by humans, so no matter how much we try and no matter how much we want to invent a striking story we fail to do that, because our thoughts are just doing circles. Thing is, how big that circle will be but eventually it all comes back to the same point. Our human brain cannot think any further than that. \r\nIf we lived in the warcraft world, Illidan's story would be a teaching of how desire and power can corrupt a pure soul.\r\nWe've got loads of examples in our world for that. Many \"Illidans\".", "date": "2008-07-30T00:15:26-05:00", "rating": -3, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}}
